
[1]samaritan

   SAMAR'ITAN, a.

   1. Pertaining to Samaria, the principal city of the ten tribes of
   Israel, belonging to the tribe of Ephraim, and after the captivity of
   those tribes, repeopled by Cuthites from Assyria or Chaldea.

   2. Denoting the ancient characters and alphabet used by the Hebrews.

                               SAMAR'ITAN, n.

   1. An inhabitant of Samaria, or one that belonged to the sect which
   derived their appellation from that city. The Jews had no dealings with
   the Samaritans.

   2. The language of Samaria, a dialect of the Chaldean.
